{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"When a required key is absent from both the file and the environment, the error message names the missing key by its exact config path (e.g., `database.host`).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is module handoff: file load + env overlay + required-key validation + CLI error formatting. A unit test of only the validator could pass while real startup wiring drops path context or checks sources in the wrong order. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: this is local config/env processing, with no required subprocess/network/real external API and no AI output dependency.","test_description":"Run the startup loader in-process with a temp config file missing `database.host` and env patched to omit `TOOL_DATABASE_HOST`; assert non-zero startup failure and that the emitted actionable error contains the exact path `database.host`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the environment variable `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is set, the loader resolves the config file path relative to that directory rather than `~/.config`.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior is about loader wiring to env-based path resolution, not just pure path-join logic. A unit test of a resolver helper can miss that startup ignores `XDG_CONFIG_HOME`. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no subprocess/network and no AI/ML decision quality; local module composition is sufficient.","test_description":"Set `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` to a temp directory, place a valid config only at `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/tool/config.yaml`, and run the real loader entrypoint; assert it loads successfully from that location and does not require `~/.config/tool/config.yaml`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When an environment variable with the `TOOL_` prefix conflicts with a key in the config file, the environment variable value is used.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at boundary between env parsing/mapping and config merge precedence. A unit test of precedence alone can miss prefix-to-key mapping or loader ordering bugs. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no OS/subprocess/network dependency beyond local in-process inputs, and no AI/ML output dependence.","test_description":"Provide a config file value (e.g., `database.host: file-host`) and conflicting env `TOOL_DATABASE_HOST=env-host`; run loader and assert effective config uses `env-host`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the config file contains a YAML syntax error, the error message includes the line number where the problem was detected.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"You must exercise real parser integration because line metadata comes from YAML parser exceptions and error translation code. Mocking parser errors can hide real line-number extraction/formatting failures. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no subprocess/network/OS-only effect required, and no AI/ML dependency.","test_description":"Create an invalid YAML config with a known syntax error line, execute loader, assert failure message includes that line number from the parser-derived error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the config directory does not exist at startup, the loader creates it and writes a defaults file before proceeding.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real OS filesystem behavior (directory creation + file write ordering at startup). In-process mocks can hide permission/path/atomicity differences and race-prone filesystem semantics. Higher AI levels are disqualified by behavior text: no AI/ML call, no agentic decision sequence.","test_description":"In an isolated real temp HOME/XDG path where config dir is absent, run startup loader and assert directory is created, defaults file is physically written at the expected path, and loader then proceeds using that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
